defaultAssociation of Professional Financial Advisersdefault – Written evidencedefault&#xa0;
defaultWhen the Department for Business, Innovation &amp; Skills consulted on whether non-economic regulators should have a duty to have regard to growth, APFA (the Association of Professional Financial Advisers) called for the newly formed financial services regulator, the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA), to be given a duty to have regard to growth and the economic impact of its actions. 
default&#xa0;
defaultIn its response to the consultation, the Government states that it believes that the duties contained in the Financial Services Act 2012 (FSA 2012) are appropriately framed for regulators of financial services, given the nature of financial services markets and their role in the economy, while being sufficiently similar in intent to the growth duty being consulted on to remove any necessity to apply it to them.
default&#xa0;
defaultHowever, APFA remains concerned, for the reasons set out in its original response, that the existing duty is insufficient and that the FCA should therefore be brought within the scope of the new duty for non-economic regulators to have regard to growth. 
default&#xa0;
defaultIn summary, we acknowledge that the FSA 2012 includes a regulatory principle that the FCA must have regard to the desirability of sustainable growth. Our concern is that the consultation envisaged a stronger duty (i.e. regulators 
defaultmustdefault consider the impact of their actions in economic terms) than that which is contained in the FSA 2012. If the FCA were to be excluded from the proposed duty, it would not be obliged to consider the economic impact of its actions, but only to 
defaulthave regard todefault the desirability of economic growth. Therefore, we believed that the FCA’s existing duty is not as strong as that proposed and that this shortcoming needed to be rectified.
default&#xa0;
defaultA copy of our original response, setting out our concerns in more detail, is attached.
